\end{align}&lt;/math&gt;}}

====Analytical questions====

The preceding analysis is algebraic, using only the commutation relations between the raising and lowering operators. Once the algebraic analysis is complete, one should turn to analytical questions. First, one should find the ground state, that is, the solution of the equation formula_36. In the position representation, this is the first-order differential equation
formula_37
whose solution is easily found to be the Gaussian
formula_38
Conceptually, it is important that there is only one solution of this equation; if there were, say, two linearly independent ground states, we would get two independent chains of eigenvectors for the harmonic oscillator. Once the ground state is computed, one can show inductively that the excited states are Hermite polynomials times the Gaussian ground state, using the explicit form of the raising operator in the position representation. One can also prove that, as expected from the uniqueness of the ground state, the Hermite functions energy eigenstates formula_39 constructed by the ladder method form a &quot;complete&quot; orthonormal set of functions.

Explicitly connecting with the previous section, the ground state |0⟩ in the position representation is determined by formula_40,
formula_41
formula_42
hence
formula_43
so that formula_44, and so on.

===Natural length and energy scales===
The quantum harmonic oscillator possesses natural scales for length and energy, which can be used to simplify the problem. These can be found by nondimensionalization.

The result is that, if &quot;energy&quot; is measured in units of and &quot;distance&quot; in units of , then the Hamiltonian simplifies to
formula_45
while the energy eigenfunctions and eigenvalues simplify to Hermite functions and integers offset by a half,
formula_46
formula_47
where are the Hermite polynomials.

To avoid confusion, these &quot;natural units&quot; will mostly not be adopted in this article. However, they frequently come in handy when performing calculations, by bypassing clutter.

For example, the fundamental solution (propagator) of , the time-dependent Schrödinger operator for this oscillator, simply boils down to the Mehler kernel,
